708998f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 54th Street (West)
708998f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, at . . 54th Street, showing St.
Lukes Hospital at the N. W. corner of same. This structure
was erected in 1858, thru the efforts of the Rev. Dr. William
A. Vuhlenberg, the rector of the Church of the Holy Communion.
He began this work in 1846 and in 1850 raised a subscription of
V100,00O. A corporation was formed and in 1854 opened an
infirmary in a Sixth Avenue house to be conducted by the Sisters
of the Holy Communion. In 1888 a Craining School for Nurses was
established. In 1892, the Trustees purchased a tract on W. 113th
Street, near tne (then) proposed Cathedral of St. John and erected
a new hospital. This site in 1w39 is occupied by the 9 story
University Club.
This view shows, a vacant lot at the S. W . corner of this
point,at the ieft of which stood for years the Rockefeller residence.
See views on 54th Street for same.
About 1859
Gift of George T. Bagoe

713705f-a.text:
54th Street, west from and inclucing Fifth Avenue, showing St.
Luke's Hospital, opened in 1859, on the north side of 54th
Street. Its front yard, at the N.W. corner of Fifth Avenue, is
the future site of the University Club. 4 East 54th Street, the
four-story house, has been built since 1862. The view is not
cuite inclusive enough to be sure, but work can hardly have more

corner of Fifth Avenue and 53rd Street.
About 1865.

708996f.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 54th Street (West)
708996f.text:
Fifth Avenue, west side, north from West 54th Street,
showing prominently Dr. Hall's Fifth Avenue Presbyter-
ian Church at the N. W. corner of 55th Street. Crgan-
ized in 1808, their first church was erected on Cedar
Street. The Pev. John Brodhead Romeyn became the first
pastor, retaining his connection with the parish until
his death in 1825. In common with all the earlier
churches, the Cedar Street parish Ihmade several removals
farther uptown; in 1834 to Duane Street; in 1852 to its
first Pifth Avenue church, at the corner of 19th Street,
when the corporate name was changed, and agalD,,ln 1875
to the present location.
To the left is St. Lukes Hospital, occupying the Avenue
frontage from 54th to 55th Street's.

708999f-a.title: Manhattan: 5th Avenue - 54th Street (West)
708999f-a.text:
Fifth Avenue, at the N.W. corner of West 54th
Street, showing St. Luke's Hospital, erected in 1858.
Begiining in 1846 under the guidance of the Rev. Dr. Wm.
A. Muhlenberg, rector of the Church of the Holy Communion,
a public appeal for funds in 1850 resulted in the formation
of a corporation and in subscriptions amounting to S100,000.
An infirmary was opened on Sixth Avenue in 1854. This
work was transfered to the newly erected hospital in
1858.
Increased demands necessitated the abandonment
of this structure and the erection of a new building
on 113th Street, near the Cathedral of St. John. The
corner stone there was laid, May 6, 1893. For further
details of this humamitarian work see pages 471-3 of
Kings Handbook of New York, 1893.
1894
Urbrock Collection

713713f-a.title: Manhattan: 54th Street (West) - 5th Avenue
713713f-a.text:
18 to 4 West 54th Street, south side, east from but not including Sixth,
to but not including Fifth Aves., showing the 9-story (No. 10) and
contiguous to it eastward, the 4-story (No. 4),Rockefeller residences.
These two houses are to be demolished and the land will be used bv the
Museum of Modern Art as a garden for the display of sculpture. It was
presented to the Museum by Mr. and Mrs, John D. Rockefeller Jr. as a
gift, shortly after the demise of the elder Rockefeller. No. 4, the
4-story residence which stands within an enclosed garden, was the residence
of John D. Rockefeller Sr. It was built in 1865 and was bought by
Mr. Rockefeller in 1895. The 9-story house, No. 10, is the residence of
John D. Rockefeller Jr. and is one of the largest private homes in the city.
It was built in 1912 at a cost of 200, 000 dollars. (For further information
see the New York Times of June 18, 1937, page 1).
December 28, 1936.
P. L. Sperr.

(1)
West 54th Street, west from Fifth Ave. On the left are
the two Rockefeller homes; that of the late John D. Sr. being

the aforementioned structures. The renovated private building

713710f-b.title: Manhattan: 54th Street (West) - 5th Avenue
713710f-b.text:
4 West 54th Street, adjoining the S.W. corner of Fifth Avenue,
showing the John D. Rockefeller Sr. home and garage as viewed eastward
towards the Avenue. According to the New York Times of May 16, 1938
the 80 year old house will be demolished, leaving the garage.
At that time no plans were announced for the improvement of this site.
Latter it became known that a garden for the new Museum of Modern Art
will be here and include the John D. Jr. home site.
May 3, 1938.
View 2: June 20, 1938.
P. L. Sper
(3)
A westward view after the aforementioned demolition and show-
ing the John D. Rockefeller Jr. home still standing. Note the clearance
to the est of same and the new Museum of Modern Art to the rear.
